"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezra chapters 8–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezra-8-10.py

Replaces the multi-book placeholder stub. Covers ch 8-10 only.

Ch 8: Ezra's second aliyah — the list of returnees, the Ahava fast, the journey
  - v1-14: Family registry of Ezra's caravan; Davidic and Aaronide lines both present
  - v15-20: Shortage of Levites; Casiphia; Nethinim as temple servant class
  - v21-23: The Ahava fast — Ezra's dilemma between his claim (God protects seekers) and need for security
  - v24-30: The priestly treasure-bearers; the enormous valuables (650 talents silver = ~24 tons)
  - v31-36: The 4-month journey; arrival; formal accounting; 12-tribe sacrifice symbolism
  - v36: Satraps and governors — the Persian administrative hierarchy in Trans-Euphrates

Ch 9: Ezra's prayer of confession
  - v1-2: The mixed-marriage report; the Deuteronomic enemy list and how it applies in the Persian period
  - v3-5: Mourning rituals (tearing clothes, pulling hair); the harēdîm (trembling ones) group
  - v6-15: The covenant-confession prayer genre; corporate-historical guilt model;
    tent-peg and wall imagery; land-contamination theology from Lev 18/Deut 7

Ch 10: The assembly and the list
  - v1-6: Shechaniah's proposal; the legal mechanism for dissolving mixed marriages
  - v7-15: The winter assembly (9th month = Kislev, rainy season); the three-month investigation process
  - v16-17: The committee system for case-by-case review
  - v18-43: The full list (priests → Levites → singers → gatekeepers → laypeople)
  - v44: The muted coda: "some of the women had already borne children"
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 8 opens the first-person memoir of Ezra (begun in 7:27), reading like an official travel journal. The list of family heads parallels the first-return list in Ezra 2 (=Neh 7), establishing this as the second great aliyah. The genealogical form signals covenant continuity: returnees identify by ancestral houses (<em>bêt ʾāḇôt</em>), the kinship unit organizing Israelite society from the pre-monarchic period. In the Persian administrative system, such genealogical registers were recognized as legal documents establishing property and community rights.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The list opens with both priestly and royal lines: &lsquo;sons of Phinehas&rsquo; and &lsquo;sons of Ithamar&rsquo; represent the two surviving Aaronide branches (Eleazar and Ithamar; Nadab and Abihu died in Lev 10:1-2). The preservation of both Aaronide lines signals the full re-establishment of the temple priesthood. &lsquo;Sons of David: Hattush&rsquo; is notable — 1 Chr 3:22 places Hattush in the post-exilic Davidic genealogy. Though no Davidic king sat on the throne, the dynasty&rsquo;s genealogical continuity was preserved across the exilic period, sustaining Messianic hope in the restoration community.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The twelve family groups in vv3-14 mirror the twelve-tribe structure, even though returnees were predominantly from Judah, Benjamin, and scattered Levites. The numbers given are &lsquo;males registered with their genealogical records&rsquo; (<em>mityaḥes</em>), meaning they demonstrated covenant identity through written genealogy. This documentary practice — covenant membership proven by records — was a Second Temple development that managed identity in a diaspora context, laying the groundwork for the later rabbinic concept of <em>yiḥus</em> (genealogical standing).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Elihoenai son of Zerahiah, with 200 males, from the sons of Pahathmoab. The theophoric name Elihoenai (&lsquo;my eyes are toward YHWH&rsquo;) reflects the piety of families maintaining their Yahwistic identity across generations in Babylon. The Murashu archive (Nippur, mid-5th century BCE, near the time of Ezra) documents hundreds of Jewish personal names in a Babylonian commercial context, confirming that Judean families maintained distinct naming practices and community identity even while participating in the Babylonian-Persian economy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The missing father&rsquo;s name in some manuscripts (&lsquo;the son of Jahaziel,&rsquo; without naming the father) reflects a textual variant between Ezra and the parallel in 1 Esdras 8:32. The uncertain genealogy of some returnees was historically plausible — records kept in Babylon across several generations had gaps. The priestly commission that adjudicated disputed lineages (Ezra 2:62; Neh 7:64) was one of the Second Temple&rsquo;s key institutions for managing covenant community boundaries in the absence of the original land and temple records.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ebed son of Jonathan, from the sons of Adin, with 50 males — the Adin clan sent 454 in the first return (Ezra 2:15) and appears in the covenant-signers of Neh 10:16. The small number in Ezra&rsquo;s second wave (50 vs. 454 earlier) illustrates the pattern of diminishing returns: the most motivated made the first aliyah; subsequent waves consisted of those with more to leave behind or who needed a specific catalyst. Ezra&rsquo;s Torah-reform mission provided such a catalyst for families who had not yet returned.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jeshaiah from the sons of Elam, with 70 males — the Elam clan was among the largest in the first return (Ezra 2:7: 1,254 members). The Murashu archive&rsquo;s documentation of Jewish families near Nippur across the 5th century BCE confirms that the exile community was economically active and demographically stable. The families who sent members back to Yehud were not necessarily the poorest; many had established economic positions in Babylonia that made the decision to emigrate genuinely costly.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Zebadiah from the sons of Shephatiah, with 80 males. The Shephatiah clan includes prominent Judean families (2 Sam 3:4: Shephatiah is one of David&rsquo;s sons by Abital). The diversity of the returning families — from Davidic, priestly, and various tribal-familial backgrounds — mirrors the social complexity of the Babylonian diaspora where Judean families maintained identity across economic classes and social positions.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Obadiah son of Jehiel from the sons of Joab, with 218 males — a substantial contingent. The Joab connection (David&rsquo;s general, 2 Sam 2:13) indicates families preserving memory of their military-noble pre-exilic origins. The numbering by males (<em>zĕkārîm</em>) reflects the ANE census practice of counting fighting-age men, but here the purpose was establishing covenant community identity rather than military mobilization. Ezra&rsquo;s caravan was a civilian mission, not a military expedition, though they carried enough wealth to attract raiders (v22).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The sons of Shelomith, with 160 males — Shelomith is named in the post-exilic Davidic genealogy (1 Chr 3:19). Multiple Davidic-line family groups in Ezra&rsquo;s caravan suggest that the restoration community carefully preserved the royal genealogy, even without a functioning monarchy. Persian Yehud under appointed governors maintained a constitutional memory of the Davidic hope — Haggai addresses Zerubbabel as the Davidic representative (Hag 2:20-23) — and the presence of these families in the aliyah reflected a shared eschatological expectation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Zechariah son of Bebai, with 28 males from the sons of Bebai — the Bebai clan numbered 623 in the first return (Ezra 2:11). The smaller second-wave number (28 of 623) illustrates the typical pattern: early returners were those most driven by religious motivation or economic necessity; later waves required specific community-building incentives like Ezra&rsquo;s Torah mission. The book of Ezra-Nehemiah repeatedly implies that the majority of Judean exiles chose to remain in Babylonia, where they had built homes and established lives (cf. Jer 29:5-7: the divine instruction to &lsquo;build houses and live in them&rsquo;).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Johanan son of Hakkatan from the sons of Azgad, with 110 males — Azgad sent 1,222 in the first return (Ezra 2:12), making the 110 in Ezra&rsquo;s wave a small fraction. The Azgad family&rsquo;s continued presence in Babylonia four generations after the initial deportation (ca. 597 BCE) illustrates successful cultural adaptation. The Murashu archive documents show Jewish families (bearing names like Tobiah, Ahijah, Hanani, Shabbethai) engaged in agriculture, commerce, and financial services throughout the Nippur region, deeply embedded in the Babylonian economy.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&lsquo;The later sons of Adonikam&rsquo; (<em>ʾaḥrônîm</em>, &lsquo;the latter ones&rsquo;) — Adonikam sent 666 in the first return (Ezra 2:13); these 60 represent the family&rsquo;s remaining portion completing their aliyah with Ezra. The term <em>ʾaḥrônîm</em> literally means &lsquo;last/latter&rsquo; and indicates this group was the final installment of the Adonikam family&rsquo;s return. Three names are given — Eliphelet, Jeiel, and Shemaiah — identifying the family leaders who organized the departure, which would have required selling property, settling accounts, and gathering the household.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Uthai and Zabbud from the sons of Bigvai, with 70 males — Bigvai sent 2,056 in the first return (Ezra 2:14), so the 70 here represent the late-returning remnant. The total of Ezra&rsquo;s caravan (adding all numbers in vv3-14) is approximately 1,496 males, plus women and children — perhaps 5,000-6,000 total, compared to approximately 49,897 in the first return (Ezra 2:64-65). The smaller size reflects both the successful assimilation of Judean families and the genuine hardship of the 1,500 km journey to an uncertain resettlement.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Ahava is probably the Nahr ʿAwān, a canal in the Babylonian irrigation network near the Chebar river (where Ezekiel received his visions, Ezek 1:1; 3:15). Canal staging areas were standard departure points for long-distance caravans in Mesopotamia — they provided water, grazing for animals, and time for organizational logistics. The three-day encampment is a preparation period typical of decisive divine-act narratives in the OT (Gen 22:4; Exod 19:11-16; Josh 3:2).</p><p>The discovery that no Levites were present was a serious problem. The first return included only 74 Levites versus 4,289 priests (Ezra 2:36-40) — a remarkably skewed ratio. Levites may have been better assimilated, lacking alternative occupational skills outside cultic service, or may have had less motivation for the Jerusalem-focused priestly restoration project.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The embassy to recruit Levites — nine &lsquo;leading men&rsquo; plus two &lsquo;men of discernment&rsquo; (<em>mĕbîn</em>) — reflects the emerging Second Temple institution of the scribe-teacher, distinct from both the priest (ritual expert) and the prophet (oracle-giver). The <em>mĕbîn</em> designation (one who gives understanding) anticipates the role of the Torah-interpreter that Ezra himself exemplifies (7:10; Neh 8:7-8). Sending trained teachers as recruitment agents reflects the social prestige that Levitical Torah-teaching was acquiring in the post-exilic period.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Casiphia (<em>Kāsipyāh</em>) is an otherwise unknown settlement — possibly derived from <em>kesef</em> (silver), perhaps indicating a merchant quarter or a community center. The phrase &lsquo;Iddo and his relatives the Nethinim at the place called Casiphia&rsquo; suggests a Levitical-Nethinim settlement or training center in Babylonia, perhaps serving as a kind of proto-synagogue or study-center for those maintaining the tradition in the diaspora.</p><p>The Nethinim (temple servants) were a distinct class of uncertain origin — possibly descendants of Gibeonites (Josh 9:21-27), war captives given to temple service (Num 31:30,47), or Solomon&rsquo;s servants (Ezra 2:55-58). They appear in the first-return list as a distinct community (Ezra 2:43-58) and in the second temple occupied a specific quarter in Jerusalem (Neh 3:26; 11:21).</p>",
    "18": "<p>&lsquo;By the good hand of our God upon us&rsquo; (<em>yad ʾĕlōhênû haṭṭôḇāh</em>) — this formula recurs throughout the Ezra-Nehemiah memoir sections (7:9,28; 8:18,22,31; Neh 2:8,18), functioning as a theological interpretive gloss on apparently fortunate outcomes. The formula is not specific about the mechanism (divine intervention, providential timing, favorable circumstances) but claims the interpretive key: the good outcome reflects YHWH&rsquo;s beneficent activity. Sherebiah from the sons of Mahli (a Levitical family descended from Merari) is specifically called a man of <em>śekel</em> (good sense, discernment) — a character evaluation unusual in the genealogical lists.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hashabiah and Jeshaiah of the sons of Merari — the Merarite clan was responsible for the heavier structural elements of the tabernacle transport (Num 3:36-37: boards, bars, pillars, bases). The total Levite recruitment was 38 individuals (Sherebiah with 18, Hashabiah with 20 relatives) — still small but sufficient to staff basic Levitical functions. The persistent shortage of Levites in the post-exilic community was a structural problem that Nehemiah also addressed (Neh 13:10-13: the Levites had returned to their fields because the temple portions were not given to them).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The 220 Nethinim represent the temple-servant class functioning below the Levites in the cultic hierarchy. The &lsquo;Nethinim whom David and the officials had appointed to assist the Levites&rsquo; — the reference to Davidic appointment claims royal authorization for the institution, possibly reflecting the tradition that David expanded the Levitical support staff (1 Chr 23:24-32). The proportion of Nethinim (220) to Levites (38) in Ezra&rsquo;s caravan suggests the Nethinim were a more stable community in the diaspora — perhaps more easily recruited because they had fewer economic assets to leave behind.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Ahava fast is one of Ezra&rsquo;s most theologically self-aware moments. The stated purpose — &lsquo;to humble ourselves before our God&rsquo; (<em>lĕhitʿannôt lipnê ʾĕlōhênû</em>) and &lsquo;to seek from him a straight way&rsquo; (<em>lĕbaqqēš derek yĕšārāh</em>) — establishes the spiritual frame for the physical journey. The <em>derek yĕšārāh</em> (straight/right road) is both a practical request (safety) and a theological claim (YHWH&rsquo;s guidance). Communal fasting as preparation for dangerous undertakings is attested throughout the OT (Judg 20:26; 2 Chr 20:3; Joel 2:12) and became a standard practice in Second Temple Judaism.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s explicit shame about asking for military protection reflects the bind his earlier theological claim had created. Having told the king &lsquo;the hand of our God is upon all who seek him for good, but the power of his wrath is against all who forsake him,&rsquo; to then request soldiers would imply either that they had forsaken him or that the claim was mere rhetoric. The Persian military escort system was standard practice for caravans carrying tribute — the roads of Trans-Euphrates were not uniformly safe. The absence of a military escort was a genuine security risk, as v31 acknowledges (&lsquo;ambushes along the road&rsquo;).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The resolution is simply stated: they fasted and prayed, and &lsquo;he answered our prayer&rsquo; (<em>wayye&lsquo;āter lānû</em>). The verb <em>ʿātar</em> (to entreat, to be entreated) is a distinctive word for answered prayer in Chronicles-Ezra (1 Chr 5:20; 2 Chr 33:13,19). The narrative brevity — one verse covers both the prayer and the answer — is characteristic of the memoir style; the theological interpretation replaces narrative detail. This editorial technique (compressing the action to foreground the theological point) is a hallmark of the Ezra memoir&rsquo;s literary method.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Twelve leading priests designated as treasure-bearers — twelve mirrors the twelve-tribe structure that runs throughout the restoration narrative (twelve bulls for Israel in v35; twelve goats at the temple dedication, 6:17; the twelve-foundation stones of the new Jerusalem). The number twelve is deliberate, emphasizing that the restoration is for all Israel even when the caravan is mostly Judahite. The weighting before departure and re-weighing upon arrival (v33-34) is the accounting procedure protecting all parties: donors, bearers, and recipients.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The contributors to the temple treasure are listed in order: king, counselors, officials, all Israel present. This inverts a tribute payment (from Israel upward to king); here the king contributes downward to Israel&rsquo;s God. The pattern follows Cyrus&rsquo; decree (1:2-4) and reflects the Persian policy of supporting local temples to secure the loyalty of subject peoples. The Cyrus Cylinder records similar provisions for Babylonian temples: &lsquo;I gathered all their inhabitants and returned to them their habitations... I set up my yoke over all of them in peace.&rsquo;</p>",
    "26": "<p>Six hundred and fifty talents of silver — approximately 22 metric tons by the Babylonian standard (about 30.3 kg per talent). The addition of &lsquo;a hundred talents&rsquo; worth of silver vessels&rsquo; — vessels valued by weight rather than named individually — shows the priestly precision in accounting. For comparison, the entire annual tribute of the satrapy of Babylon (Herodotus 3.89-94) was 1,000 Babylonian talents of silver — so 650 talents from a single community donation would represent an extraordinary concentration of wealth, though the figures in Ezra may use a lighter shekel standard.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The twenty gold bowls at a thousand drachmas (<em>darkĕmônim</em>) each reflects the mixed monetary vocabulary of the Persian period. The Greek <em>drachme</em> was already used in Persian administrative contexts by the 5th century BCE, attesting to the cosmopolitan commercial culture of the Achaemenid empire. The &lsquo;two vessels of fine burnished bronze, precious as gold&rsquo; (<em>nĕḥōšet maḥmād ṭôḇ kazzāhāḇ</em>) were probably valuable imported Eastern bronzes — possibly from Greece or Cyprus, where fine bronzework was prized. The detail of bronze &lsquo;as precious as gold&rsquo; indicates these were exceptional pieces valued for their craftsmanship, not merely their material weight.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&lsquo;You are consecrated to the LORD, and so are these vessels&rsquo; (<em>qōdeš laYHWH</em>) — Ezra applies the priestly consecration formula (used for tabernacle service items in Exod 28:36; Lev 27:28) to the mission&rsquo;s treasure-bearers. The bearers are not merely couriers but priestly guardians of holy items, with the legal implications of that role under priestly law (Lev 5:14-16: trespass offerings for violating consecrated items; Num 4:15,19-20: death for unauthorized handling of holy objects). The consecration language elevates the administrative act to a theological act.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The reference to &lsquo;chambers of God&rsquo;s house&rsquo; (<em>lĕšākôt bêt YHWH</em>) reflects the Second Temple storage rooms described throughout Ezra-Nehemiah (Neh 10:39; 12:44; 13:4-9). These treasury-chambers were major institutional features of the post-exilic temple economy, used to store tithes, contributions, and sacred equipment under priestly oversight. The chamber-system likely developed partly in response to the Persian preference for institutional accountability — the Achaemenid administration expected clear records for all funds managed by temple institutions under royal patronage.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The formal reception of the treasure by the priests and Levites completes the chain of custody: donors (Babylon) → designated bearers (Ezra&rsquo;s named priests) → temple custodians (Jerusalem priests and Levites). This chain of custody reflects both practical security (20+ tons of metal moving 1,500 km) and theological concerns about maintaining the holiness of dedicated items. The post-exilic community&rsquo;s meticulous record-keeping was partly a response to the accusations of irregularity and corruption that had characterized pre-exilic temple administration (Jer 26:10-11; Ezek 22:26).</p>",
    "31": "<p>&lsquo;The hand of our God was upon us, and he delivered us from the hands of enemies and ambushes along the road&rsquo; — the theological summary answers both the fast (v21-23) and the practical security concern (v22). The &lsquo;ambushes&rsquo; (<em>yad ʾôrēb</em>, lit. &lsquo;hand of the one lying in wait&rsquo;) were a real road-security concern in the Syrian-Palestinian corridor. The Persian Royal Road (Sardis to Susa) was patrolled, but caravan routes through the Syro-Palestinian hinterland were more vulnerable to raiding by nomadic groups, brigands, or hostile local populations.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Arrival in Jerusalem and a three-day rest before any formal activity mirrors the three-day encampment at Ahava (v15). The three-day pattern functions as a transition marker in OT narratives (arrival → rest → new phase begins). The three-day rest allowed the caravan to recover from the approximately 4-month journey (1st Nisan to 1st Ab per 7:9) before undertaking the formal accounting ceremony — a logistically sensible pause that the narrative records with the same matter-of-fact brevity as the journey itself.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Meremoth son of Uriah received the treasure on behalf of the Jerusalem community. Meremoth also built sections of the wall under Nehemiah (Neh 3:4,21) — a priestly official who served across the Ezra and Nehemiah periods, indicating a stable priestly leadership in Second Temple Jerusalem. The formal weighing ceremony is the official receipt in the Persian administrative sense — a written record protecting the bearers from any subsequent accusation of misappropriation. Persian administrative practice required documented transfers of state-adjacent funds.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&lsquo;Everything was accounted for by number and by weight; the full total was recorded at that time&rsquo; (<em>ḇaqqet hahûʾ</em>) — the contemporaneous recording is important legally: the accounting happened at delivery, not retrospectively. Persian administrative documents from this period (found in various archives from Egypt to Mesopotamia) show simultaneous accounting practices for transfers of temple equipment and treasury items. The recording &lsquo;at that time&rsquo; is the Ezra memoir&rsquo;s way of affirming the integrity of the process — no opportunity for post-hoc adjustment.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Twelve bulls for all Israel, 96 rams, 77 lambs, and 12 male goats as sin offerings — the twelve-tribe symbolism is maintained even though only a portion of the tribes returned. The sin offering (<em>ḥaṭṭāʾt</em>) placing before the burnt offerings signals that the returned exiles began with atonement, not celebration. The 12-tribe sacrificial symbolism at the beginning of each major restoration event (here; Ezra 6:17; the 12 stones at the Jordan crossing, Josh 4) is the restoration community&rsquo;s liturgical claim: the God of all twelve tribes is being re-approached on behalf of the whole people.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The satraps (<em>ʾaḥašdarpenîm</em>, from Old Persian <em>xšaçapāvan</em>, &lsquo;protector of the realm&rsquo;) and governors (<em>paḥôt</em>) of Trans-Euphrates represent two levels of the Persian administrative hierarchy. The satrapy of Abar-Nahara (&lsquo;Beyond the River,&rsquo; Trans-Euphrates) was a vast unit covering Syria, Phoenicia, and Palestine. Yehud was a sub-province (<em>mĕdînāh</em>) with its own governor. The satraps&rsquo; support — &lsquo;supporting the people and the house of God&rsquo; — reflects the practical effect of Artaxerxes&rsquo; firman (7:21-24) authorizing Ezra&rsquo;s mission and requiring cooperation from the Persian bureaucracy.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The mixed-marriage report invokes the Deuteronomic enemy list: Canaanites, Hittites, Perizzites, Jebusites (Deut 7:1-3; Exod 34:11-16), Ammonites, Moabites, Egyptians, and Amorites. By the Persian period, most of these ethnic groups had ceased to exist as distinct entities — &lsquo;Canaanites&rsquo; and &lsquo;Jebusites&rsquo; were historical categories, not contemporary populations. The list functions as a covenant-theology template: the &lsquo;peoples of the land&rsquo; are defined by their religious practices (&lsquo;abominations,&rsquo; <em>tôʿăḇôt</em>), not their ethnic descent. The actual women involved were likely from neighboring peoples of Yehud — Samaritans, Ammonites, Moabites, and various mixed-heritage groups in the region.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&lsquo;The holy offspring has mixed itself with the peoples of the land&rsquo; — <em>zeraʿ haqqōdeš</em> (&lsquo;holy seed&rsquo;) is unique to this verse in the entire OT. It develops the &lsquo;holy nation&rsquo; concept (Exod 19:6) into a genealogical framework: the covenant community is a distinct lineage defined by its relationship to YHWH. This concept anticipates the later rabbinic concern with <em>yiḥus</em> (genealogical standing) as a mark of covenant membership. The specific note that the &lsquo;officials and overseers&rsquo; led the way in the mixed marriages — not the common people — signals a structural leadership failure, which explains Ezra&rsquo;s particularly intense reaction.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s mourning gestures — tearing garment and robe, pulling hair from head and beard, sitting in shock — are ANE mourning rituals signaling extreme grief or horror. The beard was a major mark of male honor in the ancient Near East; the Assyrian reliefs show beards as the distinguishing feature of dignified men. Hanun&rsquo;s shaving of Israelite ambassadors&rsquo; beards (2 Sam 10:4-5) was an extreme public insult. Ezra&rsquo;s self-disfigurement is a calculated public act — it communicates the magnitude of the covenant disaster to everyone who sees him, before he speaks a single word.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <em>ḥārēdîm</em> (those who trembled at the words of God) who gathered around Ezra appear to be a specific group of pietists defined by their intense responsiveness to the divine word — a proto-renewal community. The phrase echoes Isa 66:5 (&lsquo;hear the word of the LORD, you who tremble at his word&rsquo;) and may reflect a circle of Isaianic disciples in the restoration community. The existence of such a distinct sub-group of Torah-devoted individuals is important for understanding Second Temple Judaism&rsquo;s development: similar circles later produced the Essenes, the Pharisees, and various other renewal movements.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The &lsquo;time of the evening offering&rsquo; (<em>minhah hāʿāreḇ</em>) — the afternoon <em>tāmîd</em> sacrifice offered around 3pm — frames Ezra&rsquo;s prayer within the daily worship rhythm of the restored temple. His prostration at the hour of the temple offering connects his personal penitential act with the corporate sacrificial system. The <em>tāmîd</em> (the daily/continual offering, Num 28:1-8) was the heartbeat of the temple liturgy — its twice-daily rhythms (morning and afternoon) structured the entire temple community&rsquo;s day. Ezra&rsquo;s prayer at this liturgically charged moment signals that his intercession is not merely personal but priestly and representational.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The prayer begins with extended shame-language: &lsquo;I am too ashamed and disgraced to lift my face to you.&rsquo; In ANE honor-shame culture, the face (<em>pānîm</em>) was the locus of honor — to lift one&rsquo;s face was to claim the right to be seen by a superior. To be unable to lift the face before a king or deity was to acknowledge disqualifying shame. Ezra&rsquo;s use of first-person plural (&lsquo;our iniquities&rsquo;) despite his personal innocence reflects the Deuteronomic concept of corporate solidarity in covenant standing, the same solidarity that shapes Daniel&rsquo;s prayer (Dan 9:4-19) and Nehemiah&rsquo;s prayer (Neh 1:6-7).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;From the days of our ancestors to this very day we have been deeply guilty&rsquo; — Ezra employs a corporate-historical guilt model treating the exile community as continuous with pre-exilic generations. The same model appears in Neh 9:6-37, Dan 9:4-19, and the Levitical prayer of Neh 9. This becomes the standard genre of Second Temple penitential prayer — the great confessions of post-exilic Judaism consistently situate the present community within the long historical narrative of repeated sin and renewed divine mercy. The result (&lsquo;into the hand of the kings of the nations&rsquo;) is the standard Deuteronomic consequence-formula for covenant violation (Deut 28:25,48; Judg 2:14).</p>",
    "8": "<p>&lsquo;A tent peg in his holy place&rsquo; (<em>yātēd</em>) — the image of a tent peg driven into solid ground as a metaphor for secure establishment appears in Isa 22:23 (Eliakim &lsquo;driven like a peg in a firm place&rsquo;) and Zech 10:4 (rulers from Judah as &lsquo;tent pegs&rsquo;). For Ezra, the small returning remnant is the <em>yātēd</em> — fragile but real. The phrase &lsquo;a brief moment of grace&rsquo; (<em>kĕmiʿaṭ rāgaʿ</em>) is a theologically precise assessment: the restoration is precarious and undeserved, and the grace is disproportionate to the sin. The &lsquo;brief moment&rsquo; characterization keeps the community from complacency — the covenant grace requires covenant faithfulness in return.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&lsquo;Though we are slaves (<em>ʿăḇādîm</em>), our God has not abandoned us in our captivity&rsquo; — the use of &lsquo;slaves&rsquo; for the Persian-period returnees reflects their real political status as subjects (<em>ʾeḇed</em>) of the Persian king. The &lsquo;wall in Judah and Jerusalem&rsquo; (<em>gādēr</em>) is a metaphorical protective enclosure given by God, predating Nehemiah&rsquo;s literal wall project. Persian imperial protection (Artaxerxes&rsquo; authorization of Ezra&rsquo;s mission) is interpreted as YHWH&rsquo;s providential provision of a protective boundary — the political and theological categories overlap in the post-exilic worldview.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;And now, our God, what can we say after all this?&rsquo; — the rhetorical question transitions from the historical survey (vv6-9) to the confession of present guilt. The prayer structure follows a standard covenant-lawsuit form: praise/acknowledgment of divine faithfulness → confession of historical violations → acknowledgment that punishment was deserved → appeal for renewed mercy. This genre appears across post-exilic literature (Neh 9, Dan 9, Ps 106) and appears to reflect a developed liturgical tradition that Ezra and his contemporaries drew from or helped create.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ezra quotes the prophetic commands on land purity: the &lsquo;polluted land&rsquo; (<em>ʾereṣ niddāh</em>) is the impurity-language of Leviticus applied to the land itself. Lev 18:24-28 describes the land as &lsquo;vomiting out&rsquo; (<em>wattāqîʾ</em>) its inhabitants when they commit the abominations of the nations; Num 35:34 prohibits polluting the land where YHWH dwells. The prophets (Ezra refers generally to &lsquo;your servant prophets&rsquo;) applied this priestly theology of land-pollution to Israel&rsquo;s covenant violations. Ezra&rsquo;s citation practice — treating the prophets as authoritative interpreters of the Mosaic law — reflects the Second Temple canon-formation process in which prophecy and law were beginning to be read as a unified corpus.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The prohibition cited (Deut 7:3: &lsquo;do not intermarry with them&rsquo;) is grounded in Deuteronomy&rsquo;s concern that foreign wives would draw husbands into worship of other gods — the paradigmatic case being Solomon (1 Kgs 11:1-8). The &lsquo;never seek their peace or prosperity&rsquo; comes from Deut 23:6 regarding Ammonites and Moabites specifically. Ezra&rsquo;s application broadens specific prohibitions into a general principle of covenant separateness (<em>qĕdôšāh</em>) for the entire restoration community — an expansion typical of Second Temple halakic interpretation, which derived general principles from specific Mosaic cases.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&lsquo;You have punished us less than our iniquities deserved&rsquo; — the theological move of claiming that the punishment was actually merciful is an important element of Second Temple theodicy. The language of &lsquo;surviving remnant&rsquo; (<em>pĕlêṭāh</em>) is the technical term for exile-survivors (Ezra 9:8,13,14,15; Neh 1:2-3), drawn from Isa&rsquo;s remnant theology (Isa 6:13; 10:20-22; 37:31-32). The remnant concept became one of Second Temple Judaism&rsquo;s most important self-understanding categories — not the whole people, but a preserved core through whom the covenant promise continued.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&lsquo;Would you not be so angry with us as to destroy us, leaving no remnant or survivor?&rsquo; — the concern about total elimination of the covenant community was not merely rhetorical. In the context of the small restoration community (perhaps 50,000 total returnees in a Yehud of limited resources), demographic survival was genuinely precarious. The Persian period saw the disappearance of many small ethnic and religious groups — the neighboring Philistines, Edomites, and various Canaanite populations ceased to exist as distinct communities. The Judean community&rsquo;s survival was a historical contingency that required deliberate community-boundary maintenance.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&lsquo;O LORD, God of Israel, you are righteous; you have left us a surviving remnant... Here we are before you in our guilt — though because of it, no one among us can stand before you&rsquo; — the prayer ends without an explicit petition, only with the statement of guilt and YHWH&rsquo;s righteousness. The lack of a specific petition (no &lsquo;therefore forgive us&rsquo;) leaves the resolution open, directing attention to what follows. The Deuteronomic theology that obedience is the required response to forgiven guilt (Deut 30:1-10) provides the frame for chapter 10&rsquo;s action: the community&rsquo;s response to the covenant crisis is not more prayer but action.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s public weeping and self-prostration (<em>mitrappēś</em>) before the house of God attracted a large assembly. In the ANE honor-shame culture, public mourning by a leader signals a community crisis and calls for community response. The &lsquo;very large assembly of Israelites — men, women, and children&rsquo; reflects the covenant assembly pattern where all members gather at moments of covenant crisis (Deut 31:12; Josh 8:35; Neh 8:2-3). The presence of women and children is particularly significant — it signals that this is a full covenant-community response, not a male-leadership gathering.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Shechaniah son of Jehiel from the family of Elam (whose members appear in vv6-7 of the return list, and whose father Jehiel is listed as an offender in v26) takes initiative with a formal legal declaration: &lsquo;We have been unfaithful (<em>māʿalnû</em>) to our God.&rsquo; The verb <em>māʿal</em> (to act faithlessly/treacherously) is the priestly trespass term for violations of sacred property (Lev 5:15; Num 5:12,27). Shechaniah frames the crisis as a priestly trespass against YHWH, not merely a social problem. His opening affirmation — &lsquo;yet even now there is hope for Israel&rsquo; (<em>yēš-miqweh lĕYiśrāʾēl</em>) — is remarkable: the confession is made together with the claim that repentance has a future.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&lsquo;Let us make a covenant with our God to send away all these foreign wives and their children&rsquo; — the proposal to divorce the foreign wives is the most legally radical element of the entire book. The legal mechanism is not specified in the text, though in Persian civil law marriage and divorce were governed by contracts. Aramaic marriage and divorce documents from this period (the Elephantine papyri, 5th century BCE Jewish community in Egypt) show that Jewish divorce required a formal written document and often included financial settlements for the wife. The reference to &lsquo;those who tremble at the commandment of our God&rsquo; identifies the <em>ḥārēdîm</em> as the community&rsquo;s authoritative conscience-group.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&lsquo;Rise up, for this task is yours to lead, and we are with you. Be courageous and act&rsquo; — Shechaniah&rsquo;s charge to Ezra uses the commissioning language of the Mosaic tradition (Deut 31:7: &lsquo;be strong and courageous&rsquo;; 1 Chr 22:13; 28:20: the same formula to Solomon). The &lsquo;we are with you&rsquo; (<em>waʾănaḥnû ʿimmāk</em>) is the covenant solidarity formula (Josh 1:17: &lsquo;as we obeyed Moses, so we will obey you&rsquo;). The formal investiture of Ezra with authority by a community spokesperson is the Second Temple form of leadership installation — not a prophetic anointing but a community commissioning.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ezra&rsquo;s formal oath-administration — putting &lsquo;the leading priests, the Levites, and all Israel&rsquo; under oath — is a legally binding commitment in both Israelite and Persian-period legal contexts. Oaths sworn in the name of YHWH created enforceable obligations in Jewish community law (Lev 5:4; Num 30; Neh 5:12-13). The three-party oath (priests, Levites, all Israel) mirrors the Sinai covenant structure and the three-party covenant renewals throughout the OT (Josh 24; 2 Chr 15; Neh 10). The formal oath-ceremony transforms Shechaniah&rsquo;s voluntary proposal into a binding community commitment.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ezra withdraws to the room of Jehohanan son of Eliashib — possibly the high priest mentioned in Neh 12:22-23, or his grandfather. The use of a priestly chamber adjacent to the temple for intense personal religious practice reflects Second Temple piety that treated the temple precincts as the appropriate location for the most serious religious observances. Ezra&rsquo;s abstinence from food and water — the most severe form of fasting — mirrors Moses&rsquo; Sinai fasts (Exod 34:28; Deut 9:9,18) and Esther&rsquo;s three-day fast (Esth 4:16), both associated with moments of maximal covenant crisis and divine-human encounter.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The proclamation throughout Judah and Jerusalem reflects the Persian administrative infrastructure available to Ezra. The ability to issue community-wide proclamations through officials and elders suggests that Ezra had de facto administrative authority alongside his priestly-scribal commission (7:25-26). The &lsquo;returned exiles&rsquo; (<em>bĕnê haggôlāh</em>, literally &lsquo;sons of the exile&rsquo;) is the technical term for the covenant community defined by their experience of exile and return, distinguishing them from &lsquo;people of the land&rsquo; who had not been exiled. This social distinction was one of the Second Temple&rsquo;s central identity markers.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The two-part penalty for non-appearance — property forfeiture and excommunication — uses striking legal vocabulary. The property forfeiture (<em>yiḥārem kol-rĕkûšô</em>) uses the root <em>ḥāram</em> (the same root as &lsquo;dedicated to destruction&rsquo; in holy war), suggesting the property would be confiscated for the temple treasury. Exclusion from the community of the returned exiles was the Second Temple equivalent of being &lsquo;cut off from Israel&rsquo; (<em>kārēt</em>, Lev 7:20) — social death in the small, tight-knit Jerusalem community. The combination of economic and social penalties reflects a sophisticated coercive system appropriate to a Persian-period sub-province.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The ninth month is Kislev (November-December), the beginning of Israel&rsquo;s rainy season. The assembly at Jerusalem &lsquo;trembling because of the matter and because of the heavy rain&rsquo; (<em>mippĕnê haddāḇār ûmippĕnê haggĕšāmîm</em>) captures the physical difficulty of the moment. The open-air plaza (<em>rĕḥôḇ bêt ʾĕlōhîm</em>) in winter rain is uncomfortable for standing assemblies, which explains the congregation&rsquo;s request (v13) for a more workable process. The convergence of moral anxiety and physical cold creates the atmosphere of crisis that drives the rapid decision-making — the community cannot simply wait for better weather.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;You have been unfaithful — you have married foreign women, adding to Israel&rsquo;s guilt&rsquo; (<em>māʿal</em> appears again, cf. v2) — Ezra&rsquo;s formal charge follows the priestly accusation formula. The framing of mixed marriages as covenant trespass against YHWH establishes the theological seriousness of what might otherwise appear a social-cultural regulation. The phrase &lsquo;adding to Israel&rsquo;s guilt&rsquo; (<em>lĕhôsîp ʿal ʾašmat Yiśrāʾēl</em>) uses the guilt-accumulation concept from ch 9 — the community stands on a narrow ledge of remaining grace, and covenant violations threaten to tip it into a renewed exile.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&lsquo;Separate yourselves from the peoples of the land and from the foreign women&rsquo; — the <em>hibdēl</em> (to separate) command is the root of the Pharisaic concept of <em>hăḇdālāh</em> (separation). Ezra uses it in the specific context of marriage, but the principle extends to the general question of how the covenant community maintains its distinctiveness within an assimilating empire. The tension between covenant boundary maintenance and economic/social integration was the defining social challenge of Second Temple Judaism, and the various Second Temple movements (Pharisees, Essenes, the Dead Sea community) all represent different strategies for resolving this tension.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The assembly&rsquo;s unanimous loud-voice response — &lsquo;Yes! We must do exactly as you have said&rsquo; — is the formal covenant-ratification formula used at Sinai (Exod 24:3,7: &lsquo;all the words that the LORD has spoken we will do&rsquo;) and subsequent covenant renewals (Josh 24:21,24; Neh 5:12; 10:28-29). The community assembly speaking with one voice is the expression of covenant consensus. The immediate modification request in v13-14 does not negate the consensus — it negotiates the implementation of a decision already made in principle.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The assembly&rsquo;s modification proposal reflects the practical impossibility of resolving 113+ mixed-marriage cases in a single cold rainy afternoon. The three objections are practical, not theological: many people involved, rainy season (logistically difficult for outdoor proceedings), and the sin &lsquo;is not something that can be resolved in a day or two.&rsquo; The proposal to use local city-by-city hearings is procedurally sophisticated, reflecting the Second Temple judicial system in which local elders functioned as a court of first instance for community disputes.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The proposal assigns work to officials with city-level hearings at &lsquo;appointed times.&rsquo; The committee of two supervisors per city for investigating each case mirrors the two-witness legal requirement of Deut 17:6 and 19:15. The systematic, case-by-case review reflects a legal seriousness that treated each marriage as a specific situation requiring individual examination. Persian-period Jewish communities at Elephantine and elsewhere show similar juridical structures — local elders adjudicating community disputes using written documentation and witness testimony.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Four men opposed the plan: Jonathan, Jahzeiah, Meshullam, and Shabbethai the Levite. Their opposition is unspecified — possibly to the divorce requirement itself, to the procedural proposal, or to the committee membership. Meshullam is possibly the same wall-builder who gave his daughter in a problematic marriage (Neh 6:18), which might explain his resistance. The record of dissent — even by a minority of four — is significant for the Second Temple&rsquo;s understanding of consensus: the decision was not genuinely unanimous despite the v12 acclamation, and the text preserves this minority record honestly.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Ezra designated specific men — heads of families — for the investigation. The formal designation (<em>wayyibbādēl</em>, &lsquo;he separated/designated&rsquo;) uses the same root as the holy separation of v11, linking the investigative process to its sacred purpose. The committee sat from the first day of the tenth month (Tebeth, December-January) for the systematic investigation. The &lsquo;first day&rsquo; is the beginning of the new month (<em>rōʾš ḥōdeš</em>), a liturgically significant day often marked by special observance — the investigation begins at a calendrically appropriate moment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The investigation was completed by the first day of the first month (Nisan, March-April) — three months for 113 cases, roughly one per day. The first day of Nisan was the date Ezra had originally set out from Babylon (7:9) — the symmetry of beginning and ending on the same calendar date frames the entire Ezra mission within the liturgical year. The thoroughness (three months) and the completion (by Nisan 1st) both demonstrate the seriousness with which the community treated the covenant restoration process.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The list of those who had married foreign women begins with the priests — as expected in this priestly-dominated book. &lsquo;From the sons of Jeshua son of Jozadak&rsquo; — Jeshua/Joshua was the high priest of the first return (Ezra 3:2; Hag 1:1; Zech 3:1). Finding offenders among the sons of the high priest reflects the depth of the problem. The requirement of a ram for the trespass offering (<em>ʾāšam</em>, v19) for those priests who pledged to send away their wives is consistent with the priestly law for trespass against sacred property (Lev 5:14-16: the <em>ʾāšam</em> was the technical trespass offering for priestly violation of consecrated things).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&lsquo;They pledged to put away their foreign wives; and acknowledging their guilt, they brought a ram from the flock for their guilt offering&rsquo; — the trespass offering combines financial restitution logic (a valuable animal substituting for the sacred property violated) with priestly atonement. Only the priests in the list are specifically said to have brought the guilt offering, reflecting the higher purity standard required of priests (Lev 21: priests must maintain greater holiness than laypeople). The pledge (<em>wayyittĕnû yādām</em>, &lsquo;they gave their hands&rsquo;) is a formal legal commitment gesture, equivalent to a signed contract in an oral-gesture culture.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Hanani and Zebadiah from the sons of Immer — the Immer clan was one of the major priestly families (1 Chr 24:14; Jer 20:1: Pashur son of Immer struck Jeremiah). The widespread presence of the mixed-marriage problem across all the major priestly houses (Jeshua, Immer, Harim, Pashur in vv18-22) indicates that the mixed-marriage practice was not peripheral or recent but had been established across the priestly leadership over time. The priestly families, whose social position depended on genealogical purity, were paradoxically among the most compromised.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Five from the sons of Harim — the Harim lay clan sent 320 in the first return (Ezra 2:32). The priestly Harim (distinct from the lay Harim of vv31-32) appears throughout Nehemiah (Neh 3:11; 10:5; 12:15). Across vv18-22, approximately 17 priests had married foreign women out of 113 total cases — roughly 15% were priests. Given the small size of the priestly community, this represents a significant proportion and explains why the priestly leadership had not already addressed the problem before Ezra&rsquo;s arrival.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Six from the sons of Pashur — the Pashur family numbered 1,247 in the first return (Ezra 2:38), making it a large priestly clan. The names listed (Elioenai, Maaseiah, Ishmael, Nethaneel, Jozabad, Elasah) all bear theophoric elements — Elioenai (&lsquo;my eyes are toward God&rsquo;), Maaseiah (&lsquo;work of YHWH&rsquo;), Nethaneel (&lsquo;God has given&rsquo;). The preservation of Yahwistic names even among those who had contracted theologically problematic marriages illustrates the complex reality of the diaspora community: covenant identity was maintained in naming practices and community affiliation even when specific covenant requirements were not observed.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Of the Levites: Jozabad, Shimei, Kelaiah (=Kelita), Pethahiah, Judah, and Eliezer. The Levite Kelaiah/Kelita appears as a covenant signer (Neh 10:10) and Torah reader/interpreter (Neh 8:7) — indicating that even Levites involved in the mixed-marriage crisis went on to become leading figures in the subsequent covenant-reform movement. This suggests the process was understood as genuinely restorative rather than permanently disqualifying — a pattern consistent with the priestly theology of atonement and restoration to service after proper cleansing.</p>",
    "24": "<p>One singer (Eliashib) and three gatekeepers (Shallum, Telem, Uri) are among the offenders. The singers (<em>mĕšôrĕrîm</em>) and gatekeepers (<em>šôʿărîm</em>) were Levitical sub-guilds responsible for the musical liturgy and security of the temple (1 Chr 23-26). That those entrusted with controlling access to the sacred precincts were among those who had crossed the social-religious boundary between holy and common is theologically ironic — and reflects the reality that guild membership and personal covenant fidelity were separate matters in the practical life of the Second Temple community.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The lay Israelite list begins with the sons of Parosh (Ezra 2:3: 2,172 members, the largest lay clan in the first return). Seven names from Parosh alone. The large number from Parosh probably reflects both the clan&rsquo;s size and the fact that larger clans provided more opportunities for exogamous marriages simply by weight of numbers. The list&rsquo;s organization by clan (<em>bêt ʾāḇôt</em>) reflects the community&rsquo;s basic administrative unit — the same clan organization that structured the wall-building (Neh 3), the covenant-signing (Neh 10), and the temple service (Neh 12).</p>",
    "26": "<p>Six from the sons of Elam — notably, Shechaniah&rsquo;s father Jehiel is listed here (v2: &lsquo;Shechaniah son of Jehiel, of the family of Elam&rsquo;; v26 lists Jehiel among the Elam offenders). The reformer&rsquo;s own father is among the offenders — a striking detail the text does not highlight or explain. This may explain the urgency of Shechaniah&rsquo;s initiative: speaking first may have been his way of demonstrating that his family&rsquo;s guilt did not prevent him from advocating for the covenant. The detail illustrates the complex familial and social dynamics underlying the formal legal proceedings.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Six from the sons of Zattu (945 in the first return, Ezra 2:8). The names include Elioenai, Eliashib, Mattaniah, Jeremoth, Zabad, and Aziza. The clan-by-clan organization of the list is the natural administrative output of the clan-organized investigation (v14: &lsquo;everyone in our cities who has married a foreign wife to appear at appointed times&rsquo;). The Second Temple community&rsquo;s use of the <em>bêt ʾāḇôt</em> (ancestral house) as the basic social unit persisted throughout the Persian and early Hellenistic periods and influenced the later synagogue&rsquo;s community-organization patterns.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Four from the sons of Bebai (623 in the first return, Ezra 2:11): Jehohanan, Hananiah, Zabbai, and Athlai. Johanan son of Bebai was in the caravan list (8:11: Zechariah son of Bebai, with 28 males). The Bebai family thus spans multiple sections of the Ezra narrative — the initial caravan, the reform proceedings, and presumably subsequent community life. This continuity of named families across the book reflects either meticulous archival records or the small-community reality where the same families repeatedly appear as significant actors.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Eight from the sons of Bani: Meshullam, Malluch, Adaiah, Jashub, Sheal, and Jeremoth. Several of these names appear in the covenant-signers of Neh 10 (Malluch: 10:4,27; Adaiah: 10:39) — again indicating that participation in the mixed-marriage crisis did not permanently disqualify one from subsequent covenant leadership. The Bani clan continues across vv34-42 with the longest single-family list in the chapter, suggesting either that Bani was one of the largest lay clans or that their cases were particularly well-documented in the community archives.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Eight from the sons of Pahathmoab — the name means &lsquo;governor of Moab,&rsquo; suggesting an ancestral connection to the Moabite region (Ezra 2:6: 2,812 members, one of the larger lay clans). The presence of a Moabite-connected family in a list that includes prohibitions against Moabite intermarriage (Deut 23:3; Ezra 9:1) creates a complex social reality: the clan may have originated from mixed heritage, making its members more likely to see intermarriage as normal. The name Bezaleel (cf. the tabernacle craftsman, Exod 31:2) preserves the memory of the great artisan in common family usage.</p>",
    "31": "<p>From the sons of Harim (lay clan, distinct from priestly Harim of v21): Eliezer, Ishijah, Malchijah, Shemaiah, and Shimeon, continuing through v32 (Benjamin, Malluch, and Shemariah). The lay Harim numbered 320 in the first return (Ezra 2:32). The names bear both Yahwistic elements (Shemaiah: &lsquo;YHWH hears&rsquo;; Shemariah: &lsquo;YHWH guards&rsquo;) and more generic theophoric names. This mixture of Yahwistic and non-Yahwistic theophoric names within the same family group is typical of the post-exilic diaspora community&rsquo;s naming practices after generations in Babylon.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Benjamin, Malluch, and Shemariah complete the Harim family entry. The name Benjamin — both tribal ancestor and common personal name — illustrates how the great patriarchal and tribal names circulated as personal names in the post-exilic community, maintaining historical memory through everyday usage. The scribal faithfulness to preserve even uncertain or garbled names in genealogical lists is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s documentary method — the lists are not edited for clarity or brevity but reproduced with archival fidelity.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Seven from the sons of Hashum: Mattenai, Mattattah, Zabad, Eliphelet, Jeremai, Manasseh, and Shimei. The Hashum clan numbered 223 in the first return (Ezra 2:19). The name Manasseh appears twice in the list (here and in v30, from Pahathmoab) — whether these were the same individual, relatives, or simply two men who bore an honored ancestral name is unclear. In the small Jerusalem community, name duplication would have been resolved by the standard ANE practice of adding patronymics or clan designations.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The extended sons-of-Bani list begins in v34 and continues through v42 — spanning nine verses and 21 names, the longest single-clan entry in the chapter. The fragmented distribution across nine verses may reflect the order in which the cases were processed (alphabetically, by sub-clan, or by date of investigation) or a division of the large Bani clan into sub-groups. The list&rsquo;s length is itself a historical datum: the Bani family was either numerically the largest lay clan or their records were the most thoroughly preserved.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Bedeiah, Chelluh, and Vaniah from the sons of Bani. The name Chelluh (<em>Kelûhî</em>) and Vaniah (<em>Wanyāh</em>) are not found elsewhere in the OT, reflecting the diverse name-pool of the Babylonian diaspora where Aramaic, Babylonian, and Hebrew naming conventions mixed. The non-standard names attest to the historical reality of the diaspora community&rsquo;s cultural interaction with Babylonian-Persian naming while maintaining covenant identity. Such name-evidence is archaeologically valuable: it documents the social integration of Jewish families into the broader Mesopotamian culture without loss of Jewish identity.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Meremoth and Eliashib from the sons of Bani — the name Meremoth also appears in v33 (Meremoth son of Uriah, who received the treasure from Ezra). The same name used for a trusted priestly official and a lay offender in the same book illustrates the name-reuse common in the post-exilic period. The fragmented distribution of the Bani names across nine verses may also reflect different scribal sources being combined — portions of the original list from different city-records being assembled into the final document.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Mattenai, Mattaniah, and Jaasau from the sons of Bani. The names Mattenai (&lsquo;given&rsquo;) and Mattaniah (&lsquo;gift of YHWH&rsquo;) are among the most common post-exilic names — attested in the Murashu archive, in Nehemiah&rsquo;s lists, and in multiple places throughout Chronicles-Ezra-Nehemiah. The frequency of &lsquo;gift&rsquo; names (Mattaniah, Elnathan, Jonathan, Nethaneel) in the post-exilic community may reflect a theology of gratitude for survival — the returned exiles understood their existence as a divine gift.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Binnui and Shimei from the extended Bani list. Binnui (&lsquo;being built/son of&rsquo;) is a post-exilic name found in the wall-builders (Neh 3:24; 10:9; 12:8). The recurrence of names across Ezra-Nehemiah (same names in the Ezra 10 reform list, the Neh 10 covenant-signers, and the Neh 3 wall-builders) creates a picture of a small, tightly interconnected community where the same individuals and families appear across multiple community events spanning several decades of the Persian period.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Shelemiah, Nathan, and Adaiah from the extended Bani list. Nathan is a royal-prophetic name (2 Sam 7:2; 12:1) now used as a common post-exilic personal name — the great prophetic figures of the monarchy period entered the name-pool of the restoration community. Adaiah (&lsquo;YHWH adorns/witnesses&rsquo;) appears frequently in both Chronicles and Ezra-Nehemiah, one of the most popular theophoric names of the period. The community maintained Yahwistic name-identity even when some covenant practices had lapsed.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Machnadebai, Shashai, and Sharai from the sons of Bani. Machnadebai (<em>Maḵnaḏĕḇay</em>) is a hapax legomenon — unique to this verse in the entire OT, possibly a corrupted or Aramaized name. The list&rsquo;s inclusion of rare and uncertain names reflects scribal faithfulness to the original registration records: the scribes preserved names they could not confidently identify rather than harmonizing them. This archival fidelity is one of the reasons modern scholars regard the Ezra 10 list as historically reliable despite the challenges it raises.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Azareel, Shelemiah, and Shemariah from the sons of Bani. The list&rsquo;s enormous length (nine verses for Bani alone) contrasts sharply with the one- or two-name entries for other clans. The disproportion may reflect the actual demographics of the restoration community — if Bani was indeed one of the largest lay families, a proportionally larger number of mixed marriages would be expected — or it may reflect better archival preservation for that particular clan&rsquo;s investigation records.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Shallum, Amariah, and Joseph complete the sons of Bani. Joseph — the patriarch sold into Egypt who preserved his people through his suffering — became a popular personal name in the post-exilic community. The irony of a Bani-clan Joseph appearing in a list of mixed-marriage offenders is unintended by the text but not lost on a reader familiar with Joseph&rsquo;s own famous near-compromise with Potiphar&rsquo;s wife (Gen 39). Amariah (&lsquo;YHWH says/speaks&rsquo;) is a name common to priestly families (1 Chr 6:7,11,52) but here used by a lay Israelite.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Seven from the sons of Nebo: Jeiel, Mattithiah, Zabad, Zebina, Jaddai, Joel, and Benaiah. The Nebo clan (Ezra 2:29: 52 members) is one of the smaller families. The name Nebo — the Babylonian god Nabu (patron deity of scribes and wisdom in the Mesopotamian pantheon) — is a striking clan name for a Jewish family, reflecting how Babylonian personal names and toponyms were absorbed by the exile community. Nabu was so pervasive in Babylonian culture that Jewish families sometimes bore his name (compare the Babylonian name elements in Nebuchadnezzar, Nebuzaradan, and Abednego/Abed-Nego).</p>",
    "44": "<p>&lsquo;All of these had married foreign women; and some of the women had already borne children&rsquo; — the brief, understated final verse is the chapter&rsquo;s coda and the book of Ezra&rsquo;s conclusion. The human cost of the covenant enforcement — marriages dissolved, children separated from fathers (or mothers?) — is acknowledged without elaboration. The text does not record whether the dismissed women received divorce documents, financial settlement, or reintegration into their families of origin. Aramaic divorce documents from Elephantine (5th century BCE Jewish community in Egypt) show that Jewish divorce required a formal declaration and typically included provisions for the wife — but Ezra 10 is silent on these details.</p><p>The book ends not with triumph but with a bare list and a muted acknowledgment of human cost. The covenant has been affirmed; the people have acted; the community&rsquo;s future has been secured through painful boundary enforcement. The unresolved human dimension — the children who lost fathers, the women who lost households — remains as an open question that the text does not answer and that the later tradition found deeply uncomfortable (the book of Ruth, written to defend a Moabite woman&rsquo;s covenant inclusion, stands as the canonical counterweight to the Ezra 10 principle).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ezra')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ezra', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'Ezra 8-10 mkt-context written ({total} verses: ch8={len(CONTEXT["8"])}, ch9={len(CONTEXT["9"])}, ch10={len(CONTEXT["10"])}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
